    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper studies how a heavy quantum field oscillates when perturbed near a charged black hole that includes an extra \"dilaton\" scalar field motivated by string theory. The review board found the core trend \u2014 that heavier fields produce longer-lived oscillations, and that the dilaton coupling measurably shifts the spectrum \u2014 to be plausible and incrementally useful for gravitational-wave physics. However, the strongest conclusion, that oscillations can become arbitrarily long-lived at a precise critical field mass, is inferred by extrapolating beyond the regime where the computational method is reliable, without independent verification from a different approach. The paper would need that independent check before its boldest claims can be accepted.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper applies high-order WKB\u2013Pad\u00e9 (orders 14 and 16) and Gundlach-Price-Pullin time-domain integration to massive scalar quasinormal modes of Einstein-Maxwell-dilaton (EMD) black holes for dilaton couplings \u03b1 = 0, 1, \u221a3. The well-validated result is that dilaton-induced spectral shifts dominate the WKB numerical uncertainty by roughly two orders of magnitude (~35\u201345% shift vs. ~0.1\u20130.5% order-difference), and that damping suppression with increasing scalar mass \u03bc is clear in the l=1 sector, with sub-percent WKB\u2013time-domain agreement (0.16% and 0.45% in complex-frequency norm). The contested result is the claim of quasi-resonances (Im(\u03c9) \u2192 0 at critical \u03bc): this follows from extrapolated cubic splines beyond the demonstrably reliable WKB regime and not from a convergent near-axis method. Persistent cross-review concerns: (a) massive-field boundary conditions near the scalar mass threshold \u03c9 \u2248 \u03bc are not stated precisely enough to distinguish outgoing QNMs from quasi-bound states; (b) a claimed purely real frequency in the l=0, \u03b1=\u221a3 sector lacks time-domain verification and is potentially a WKB breakdown artifact; (c) all time-domain benchmarks cover only the l=1 sector, leaving the l=0 sector, where the most prominent quasi-resonance claims appear, without independent validation."
